     1	//! Unified REML/LAML evaluator.
     2	//!
     3	//! This module provides a single implementation of the outer REML/LAML objective,
     4	//! gradient, and Hessian that is shared across all backends (dense spectral,
     5	//! sparse Cholesky, block-coupled) and all families (Gaussian, GLM, GAMLSS,
     6	//! survival, link wiggles).
     7	//!
     8	//! # Architecture
     9	//!
    10	//! The REML/LAML formula is invariant to the sparsity
    11	//! pattern, block structure, and family type. It is always:
    12	//!
    13	//! ```text
    14	//! V(ρ) = −ℓ(β̂) + ½ β̂ᵀS(ρ)β̂ + ½ log|H| − ½ log|S|₊ + corrections
    15	//! ```
    16	//!
    17	//! What differs across backends is how the inner solver finds β̂, how
    18	//! logdet/trace/solve operations dispatch (dense eigendecomposition vs sparse
    19	//! Cholesky vs block-coupled), and what family-specific derivative information
    20	//! is available.
    21	//!
    22	//! This module separates those concerns:
    23	//! - [`HessianOperator`]: backend-specific linear algebra (logdet, trace, solve)
    24	//! - [`InnerSolution`]: the converged inner state (β̂, penalties, factorization)
    25	//! - [`reml_laml_evaluate`]: the single formula, written once
    26	//!
    27	//! # Spectral Consistency Guarantee
    28	//!
    29	//! The `HessianOperator` trait ensures that `logdet()` (used in cost) and
    30	//! `trace_hinv_product()` (used in gradient) are computed from the same
    31	//! internal decomposition. This eliminates the class of bugs where cost uses
    32	//! Cholesky-based logdet while gradient uses eigendecomposition-based traces
    33	//! with a different numerical threshold.
    34	//!
    35	//! # Trace-Estimation Tiers
    36	//!
    37	//! Several REML/LAML/PIRLS quantities reduce to traces of operators that
    38	//! have efficient HVPs but expensive dense materialization. The codebase
    39	//! picks among three estimators depending on the operator's structure and
    40	//! the problem size; backends override the default trait method to take
    41	//! the cheapest path natively when one exists.
    42	//!
    43	//! ## Tier 1: Exact (default for small p, native overrides for large p)
    44	//!
    45	//! When the operator is small enough that materializing it as a dense
    46	//! `p × p` matrix and summing the diagonal of `H⁻¹ M` is cheap, OR when a
    47	//! backend has a structure-aware exact path (e.g. Takahashi-selected
    48	//! inverse for sparse Cholesky), use it. Examples: every concrete
    49	//! `HessianOperator` impl below overrides `trace_hinv_operator` and the
    50	//! cross-trace family with a native exact path.
    51	//!
    52	//! ## Tier 2: Hutchinson (multi-target shared-probe)
    53	//!
    54	//! When the same `H⁻¹` solve serves multiple coordinate targets — the
    55	//! REML/LAML rho-gradient computes `tr(H⁻¹ A_k)` for `k = 1, ..., K` —
    56	//! [`StochasticTraceEstimator`] runs Girard–Hutchinson with one shared
    57	//! `H⁻¹` solve per probe and adaptive Welford-style stopping. Common
    58	//! random numbers (deterministic seed) hold across rho coordinates, so
    59	//! each probe contributes coherently to every coordinate's gradient.
    60	//! Triggered for very large `p` via [`can_use_stochastic_logdet_hinv_kernel`].
    61	//!
    62	//! ## Tier 3: Hutch++ (single-target, HVP-only operator)
    63	//!
    64	//! When a single trace `tr(H⁻¹ M)` is needed against an HVP-only
    65	//! operator and `p ≥ 128`, [`hutchpp_estimate_trace_hinv_operator`]
    66	//! splits the trace via Meyer–Musco's randomized range finder. The
    67	//! sketch captures the dominant subspace of `H⁻¹ M` exactly; the
    68	//! Hutchinson residual handles the orthogonal complement with greatly
    69	//! reduced variance. Achieves `O(1/ε)` matvecs vs `O(1/ε²)` for plain
    70	//! Hutchinson.
    71	//!
    72	//! [`hutchpp_estimate_trace_hinv_op_squared`] handles the symmetric
    73	//! same-operator cross-trace `tr((H⁻¹A)²)` (used by outer-Hessian
    74	//! diagonals); [`hutchpp_estimate_trace_hinv_operator_cross`] handles
    75	//! the asymmetric `tr(H⁻¹A_L H⁻¹A_R)` via a shared sketch. Default
    76	//! impls of [`HessianOperator::trace_hinv_operator`],
    77	//! [`HessianOperator::trace_logdet_operator`], and the cross-trace
    78	//! family auto-select Hutch++ for implicit operators at moderate
    79	//! `dim()`. Concrete backends with native paths (dense spectral,
    80	//! Takahashi Cholesky) override and never reach Hutch++.
    81	//!
    82	//! ## Why these three and not more
    83	//!
    84	//! The BMS / survival-marginal-slope row-trace path is *not* a
    85	//! Hutch++ candidate even though it computes a trace. The exact
    86	//! per-row algebra exploits a rank-r factor projection plus linearity
    87	//! in the rho direction to compute one length-r vector per row that
    88	//! serves all rho coordinates; a probe-based estimator would require
    89	//! `O(m · k_directions)` row passes vs the existing single row pass.
    90	//! See `bernoulli_marginal_slope::row_primary_third_trace_gradient_with_moments`.
    91	//!
    92	//! ## Orthogonal axis: row subsampling for biobank-scale fits
    93	//!
    94	//! Trace estimators here reduce work *within* the Hessian structure
    95	//! for a fixed row set. The marginal-slope families have a separate,
    96	//! complementary mechanism that reduces the row set itself: stratified
    97	//! Horvitz–Thompson outer-score subsampling (see
    98	//! `families::marginal_slope_shared`). The two compose naturally — a
    99	//! Hutch++ trace against an `H⁻¹ M` operator stays valid when `M` is
   100	//! itself a partial-row sum, and the row subsample's variance bound
   101	//! is independent of the trace estimator used inside the per-row work.
